\f + \fr 2:2\ft Espousals. He speaks ironically. (Theodoret) --- Yet the Israelites at first shewed greater proofs of love than they did afterwards. It is true they often prevaricated, in the wilderness, Exodus 32:1., and Amos 5:25., and Psalm lxxvii., etc. (Calmet) --- The Lord declares his gratuitous love, and then upbraids his people. (Haydock) --- He had caused them to multiply in Egypt, and gratuitously made choice of them. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 2:3\ft Increase; most desirable, Osee 9:10. God punished those who attempted to injure his people: yet they abandoned his service.\f*
\f + \fr 2:5\ft Vanity; idols, whom he will not mention, to spare their shame. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 2:7\ft Carmel. That is, a fruitful, plentiful land. (Challoner) (Worthington) --- All Palestine is thus designated. (Menochius)\f*
\f + \fr 2:8\ft Priests were silent, or abandoned themselves. --- Pastors; "princes." (Chaldean) Manasses, Amon, etc. --- In Baal, promoting his worship. (Haydock) --- The land was full of false prophets, and none stood up for the Lord.\f*
\f + \fr 2:9\ft Children; the Israelites, under Moses, and their posterity transgressed.\f*
\f + \fr 2:10\ft Cethim; Macedon. It here denotes the western nations, as Cedar does those on the east.\f*
\f + \fr 2:11\ft Glory; the true God and his ark, Psalm 3:4., and 1 Kings 4:21.\f*
\f + \fr 2:12\ft Gates; angels, or the temple.\f*
\f + \fr 2:13\ft Water. The idols and nations, to which they have had recourse, injure them. (Calmet) --- The Jews did just the reverse to what God commanded. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 2:14\ft Slave. From such, labour and tribute were required, Matthew 17:24., and John 8:33.\f*
\f + \fr 2:15\ft Lions; kings of Assyria, etc. The decree for the devastation of Juda had already passed, though it was not put in execution.\f*
\f + \fr 2:16\ft Taphnes, 16 miles from Pelusium, in Egypt. The nation proved only detrimental to the Jews, by engaging them in their abominations, instead of affording relief.\f*
\f + \fr 2:18\ft Troubled. Hebrew shichor, or Nile water, (Josue 13:3.) which was thought as good as wine, and grew better for keeping. (Strabo xvii.) --- Hence the people adored it. (Vitruvius viii.) --- God often reproached the Jews for distrusting in his protection, and seeking aid from the Egyptians, who deceived them. We know not that Josias did so. (Calmet) --- He even opposed them, and lost his life in defending the country, 4 Kings 23:29. (Haydock) --- He was probably obliged to pay tribute to the Assyrians, whom Achaz had called in, 2 Paralipomenon 28:23. These alliances the Lord condemned.\f*
\f + \fr 2:20\ft Thou. Septuagint. Yet Hebrew and Chaldean have, "I have permissively broken," or foretold this infidelity.\f*
\f + \fr 2:21\ft Chosen. Hebrew, Sorek, Judges 16:4., and Isaias 5:2., and 16:8. (Calmet) --- God created all things good, planted his Church in justice, and no evil proceeds from Him. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 2:22\ft Borith. An herb used to clean clothes, and take out spots and dirt, (Challoner) like kali, soda, (Calmet) or soap. (Langius.) --- Protestants, "and take thee much soap." (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 2:23\ft Valley of Hinnom, under the very walls of Jerusalem. (Calmet) --- Runner. Hebrew, "dromedary," which takes its name from its swiftness. (Haydock) --- The female camel continues all day with the male, and cannot be approached. (Aristotle; Pliny, [Natural History?] 10:63.) --- Juda is represented as no less libidinous. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 2:24\ft Away. The female may easily be found by the poisonous hippo-manes. (Georg. iii.) --- Thus Jerusalem is an impudent prostitute. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 2:25\ft Foot, and the parts which modesty covers. My exhortations are slighted. (Calmet) --- Despair opens the door to every sort of impurity, Ephesians 4:19. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 2:26\ft Taken. Juda affected still to be very pious, ver. 23.\f*
\f + \fr 2:28\ft Cities. All were abandoned, Ezechiel 16:24., and Osee 10:1.\f*
\f + \fr 2:30\ft Prophets; Zacharias, (2 Paralipomenon 24:21.) Isaias, etc., Matthew 23:34. (Calmet) --- Punishment is designed by God to cause people to repent. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 2:31\ft See, or hear. The sword seems to be animated. (Calmet) --- Lateward. Hebrew, "darksome land." Have I not heaped blessings on my people? --- Revolted. Protestants, "Lords." (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 2:33\ft Thou who. Hebrew, "Therefore have I." (Calmet) --- Protestants, "hast thou also taught the wicked ones thy ways." (Haydock) --- Thou hast opened a school of vice.\f*
\f + \fr 2:34\ft Innocent children, immolated to Moloc, or people murdered, whose blood thou hast not concealed, 4 Kings 21:16.\f*
\f + \fr 2:37\ft Head, like the violated Thamar, 2 Kings 13:19. The king of Egypt was routed, when coming to assist Sedecias, Jeremias 37:3, 10. (Calmet)\f*
