\f + \fr 4:1\ft Blocks; idols, (Calmet) and other occasions of sin. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 4:2\ft Swear, when requisite. (Calmet) --- Thus thou wilt learn to confess one God. (Theodoret) --- If all were upright, oaths would be unnecessary, Matthew 5:34. But as they are not so, (Calmet) this may be a religious act. (Worthington) --- Justice. These three conditions are essential. (Haydock) --- Him; the people, (Calmet) or God. (St. Jerome) --- An oath must attest God, and be used when a thing is true and of moment. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 4:3\ft Thorns. Your misconduct hinders your advancement. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 4:4\ft Hearts. Understand, and act with purity. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 4:5\ft Cities. Nabuchodonosor is at hand.\f*
\f + \fr 4:7\ft Robber. Nabuchodonosor attacks unjustly, (Calmet) though he be God's scourge.\f*
\f + \fr 4:9\ft Heart; counsel and vigour. --- Prophets of falsehood.\f*
\f + \fr 4:10\ft Alas! Protestants, "Then I said: Ah! Lord God, surely thou hast deceived," etc., (Haydock) by permitting the people to follow false prophets, Isaias 61:17., and Psalm 43:19.\f*
\f + \fr 4:11\ft Desert of Arabia. It may designate Nechao, (2 Paralipomenon 35:20.) who slew Josias, after whose death all fell to ruin.\f*
\f + \fr 4:15\ft Ephraim. At Bethel and Dan the calves were adored. (Calmet) --- But they were now no more. (Haydock) --- The irruption of Nabuchodonosor is announced. He set himself up for a god.\f*
\f + \fr 4:16\ft Guards. The Chaldeans will besiege the city, and prevent provisions from entering, 4 Kings 25:1. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 4:19\ft My. God, (St. Jerome) the people, (Grotius) or rather Jeremias speaks.\f*
\f + \fr 4:20\ft Moment. The cities are destroyed as easily as a tent.\f*
\f + \fr 4:22\ft Me, practically. They have not honoured me as they ought. (Calmet) --- If they were indeed devoid of sense, they would be excused. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 4:23\ft Void. Hebrew, "Thohu and bohu," like chaos, Genesis 1:2. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 4:25\ft Gone. Beasts feel the wrath of God, and in a land uninhabited; not even birds will remain, Osee 4:3. (St. Jerome)\f*
\f + \fr 4:26\ft Carmel: the beautiful country of Palestine, (Haydock) Jerusalem, (Theodoret) or the mountain so called.\f*
\f + \fr 4:27\ft Destroy, when Jechonias was led captive. God allowed the people still eleven years to repent; and he afterwards restored the Jews. (Calmet) --- He will never suffer his church to perish. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 4:28\ft Repented. Only a finite being can do this. God's resolution is here unconditional and fixed.\f*
\f + \fr 4:30\ft Stone, or antimony, like Jezabel, (4 Kings 9:30.) to darken and enlarge the eye-lids. --- Lovers. Infidel nations of Egypt, etc.\f*
\f + \fr 4:31\ft Child. Hebrew and Septuagint, "a first-born," when the pains are most acute. (Calmet)\f*
