\f + \fr 18:2\ft Potter's. Thus God would shew his dominion over all, Romans 9:21.\f*
\f + \fr 18:3\ft Wheel. Hebrew, "stones." Septuagint, "seats;" or "wheel." (Chaldean) (Exodus 1:16.) See Ecclesiasticus 38:32. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 18:4\ft Broken. So Providence ordered it. (St. Jerome) --- How should this idea humble man! (Calmet) --- A potter may mould afresh the clay as long as it is soft, but God can change the hardest heart. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 18:8\ft Shall repent, having free-will, though prevented by grace. (St. Jerome)\f*
\f + \fr 18:12\ft Hopes. Jeremias 2:25. Septuagint, "we are valiant men." (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 18:13\ft Virgin. The disorders of Israel are thus enhanced. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 18:14\ft Snow. It continues on Libanus seven or eight months, (La Roque quoted. Univ. Hist. 2:p. 363) or all the year; (Tacitus, Hist. 5:6.) and hence the mountain is justly denominated "white," as the Alps and Albion are from albon. (Bochart; Parkhurst, p. 155.) (Haydock) --- Away. Yet my people abandon me, to serve idols! Hebrew may have many other senses to the same purpose. Septuagint, "Shall the mountain springs fail, or snow from Libanus? Shall a stream forcibly driven by the wind, turn aside?" (Haydock) --- The laws of nature are observed by inanimate things, and shall my people be so foolish as to follow mere vanity.\f*
\f + \fr 18:15\ft Ancient; followed by the patriarchs, Jeremias 6:16.\f*
\f + \fr 18:16\ft Head, through contempt (Calmet) and pity, Lamentations 2:15.\f*
\f + \fr 18:17\ft Burning. Hebrew kadim, "eastern," (Haydock) coming from Desert Arabia, Exodus 10:13. (Calmet) --- Back. Thus the Lord now treats the synagogue. (St. Jerome)\f*
\f + \fr 18:18\ft Prophet. Jeremias will not cease to upbraid us with our transgressions; or we have guides as good as him, and we shall not be left destitute, as he would intimate. --- Tongue, detraction; or make him suffer for what he says. In all the transactions of this prophet, Christ was foreshewn; (Calmet) and here, particularly, the Jews demand the crucifixion. (St. Jerome) (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 18:20\ft Remember, etc. This is spoken in the person of Christ, persecuted by the Jews, and prophetically denouncing the evils that should fall upon them in punishment of their crimes. (Challoner) --- Jeremias had prayed earnestly for the people, Jeremias 14:17. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 18:21\ft Therefore. He foretells of the event, and approves of the chastisement of the impenitent, (Calmet) whose "impurity might be a bad precedent for others.["] (St. Jerome) See Jeremias 17:18.\f*
\f + \fr 18:22\ft For. Protestants, "when." (Haydock) --- Robber. So Nabuchodonosor and all professional conquerors are styled. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 18:23\ft Destroy. Hebrew, "with them." Use them as vessels of ignominy: abutere. (Haydock)\f*
