\f + \fr 23:1\ft Pastors. Successors of Josias (Calmet) and false prophets. (Menochius)\f*
\f + \fr 23:3\ft Multiplied. The prophets subjoin tidings of peace to such as might cause affliction. (Theodoret)\f*
\f + \fr 23:4-5\ft Pastors; Zorobabel, etc., as figures of Christ, and of the pastors of his Church. --- No more, as much as formerly. So many expressions must be understood. --- Branch. Septuagint, "orient." --- Reign. Zorobabel was not chief governor, (Calmet) though at the head of his tribe. (Haydock) --- The kingdom of Christ was not of this world, John 18:36. (Calmet) --- He alone imparts justice to others. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 23:6\ft Saved: less disturbed. The world shall be redeemed, Luke 2:14., and Ephesians 2:14. --- Just. Hebrew, "Justice," by whom we are made just. He is the true God, Colossians 2:9, 14. No man could bear this title: and Grotius insidiously attempts to apply it to the Jews, though the Chaldean, etc., clearly speak of the Messias. He [Grotius] must be read with great caution. (Calmet) --- Septuagint, "This is his name, which the Lord will call him, Josedech. In the prophets. (9.) My," etc. (Haydock) --- Josedech means "the Lord justice." (Calmet) --- Symmachus, "Lord, justify us."\f*
\f + \fr 23:8\ft Land. The deliverance from Egypt and Babylon were emblems of man's redemption, which was accomplished by far greater miracles.\f*
\f + \fr 23:9\ft Prophets of falsehood. He directs his discourse to them, and afterwards to the priests, being filled with amazement at their impending ruin.\f*
\f + \fr 23:10\ft Adulterers; impostors or idolaters. --- Cursing of the Lord, or the abuse of his sacred name. (Calmet) --- Unlike. Hebrew, "not right." (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 23:11\ft Defiled. Hebrew, "hypocrites." My priests retain the appearance of religion, to join with impostors in deluding the people.\f*
\f + \fr 23:14\ft Jerusalem. These were far worse, as they pretended to be inspired by God, whereas those of Samaria publicly adhered to Baal; so that the people must have been foolish to have been deceived by them. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 23:15\ft Gall, or something mortally bitter, Jeremias 9:15. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 23:16\ft Own. To rely on private judgment, and not on the Church, is a mark of falsehood. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 23:17\ft Blaspheme. Hebrew, "despise;" or Septuagint, "reject disdainfully the word of the Lord, you," etc., Jeremias 6:14., and 8:11.\f*
\f + \fr 23:18\ft Counsel. Hebrew, "secret." Which of you is acquainted with his designs? I will inform you, that your perdition is at hand, ver. 20. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 23:21\ft Not send. The want of mission proves a prophet or preacher to be false. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 23:22\ft I should. Some copies read avertissent, "they would have turned," conformably with the Hebrew, etc., and we should suspect that this was a mistake of the transcriber, if St. Jerome did not agree with the Vulgate in his commentary, (Calmet) though not in express terms: (Haydock) "I also should not have abandoned them to impurity....Let us behold how heretics, having once given way to despair,...seek the gratification of their sensual appetite." (St. Jerome)\f*
\f + \fr 23:23\ft Off? Can you so easily penetrate my designs, or escape my fury? Am I like your idols of yesterday? Septuagint and Theodotion, "I am a God at hand," etc., which agrees with the sequel. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 23:27\ft Dreams, as if God had favoured them with his revelations. (Haydock) --- Fathers; the false prophets of Baal, whom these imitate.\f*
\f + \fr 23:28\ft Dream, to those who are really sent by God, (Calmet) and recognized, 1 Corinthians 14:29. (Haydock)\f*
\f + \fr 23:29\ft Pieces? True prophets will have a zeal fo the conversion of souls, Jeremias 20:9., and Hebrews 4:12.\f*
\f + \fr 23:30\ft Neighbour, causing those whom I have sent to be disregarded.\f*
\f + \fr 23:31\ft Use. Hebrew also, "sharpen, or render smooth," and insinuating, Psalm 49:16. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 23:32\ft Wonders. Protestants, "lightness." Septuagint, "frauds," or pretended miracles. (Haydock) --- False prophets cannot work true miracles: but it is more difficult to distinguish these than the former mark of being lawfully sent, ver. 21. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 23:33\ft Burden, Massa, (Haydock) denotes a weight, or sometimes a prediction. (Calmet)\f*
\f + \fr 23:34\ft Burden of the Lord. This expression is here rejected and disallowed, at least for those times: because it was then used in mockery and contempt by the false prophets, and unbelieving people, who ridiculed the repeated threats of Jeremias under the name of his burdens. (Challoner)\f*
\f + \fr 23:35\ft Answered. I will make you alter your language by chastisements.\f*
\f + \fr 23:39\ft Take. Hebrew of the Masorets, (Calmet) "I, even I, will utterly forget (Protestants; Haydock) or abandon you." (Chaldean) But the sense of the Septuagint and Vulgate seems preferable. (Calmet)\f*
