\c 45
\cl Jeremias 45
\cd The prophet comforts Baruch in his affliction.
\p
\v 1 The word that Jeremias, the prophet, spoke to Baruch, the son of Nerias, when he had written there words in a book, out of the mouth of Jeremias, in the fourth year of Joakim, the son of Josias, king of Juda, saying:
\p
\v 2 Thus saith the Lord, the God of Israel, to thee, Baruch:
\p
\v 3 Thou hast said: Woe is me, wretch that I am, for the Lord hath added sorrow to my sorrow; I am wearied with my groans, and I find no rest.
\p
\v 4 Thus saith the Lord: Thus shalt thou say to him: Behold, them whom I have built, I do destroy; and them whom I have planted, I do pluck up, and all this land.
\p
\v 5 And dost thou seek great things for thyself ? Seek not; for behold I will bring evil upon all flesh, saith the Lord: but I will give thee thy life, and save thee in all places whithersoever thou shalt go.
\f + \fr 45:1\ft Book, which Joakim burnt, and sought the life of the prophets, Jeremias 36. (Calmet) --- Baruch apprised of the general distress, weeps for it, and his life is spared. (Worthington)\f*
\f + \fr 45:5\ft Great: the spirit of prophecy; (Rabbins) or rather to be exempted from suffering, while all the neighbouring nations were perishing. (Calmet) --- And save. Literally, "for salvation." Hebrew, "booty." (Haydock) --- He seems to have been set at liberty with his master, Jeremias 40:1. (Calmet)\f*
